Hong Kong Stocks Fluctuate as Developers Advance, HSBC Declines

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-03-01T02:35:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/hong-kong-stocks-fluctuate-as-developers-advance-hsbc-declines.html
  Hong Kong  stocks fluctuated as
developers gained after an economic report signaled China’s
moves to tame inflation may be working, while  HSBC Holdings Plc 
and Aluminum Corp. of  China  Ltd. fell after their profits missed
analyst estimates.  China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd., controlled by the
nation’s construction ministry, gained 1.7 percent on
speculation inflation eased after a report showed manufacturing
expanded at the slowest pace in six months, reducing the need
for further interest-rate increases. HSBC Holdings Plc, Europe’s
biggest bank by market value, sank 4.8 percent and Aluminum Corp.
of China Ltd., the country’s largest producer of the metal, slid
1.8 percent after they reported profits that missed analyst
estimates.  The Hang Seng Index rose 0.2 percent to 23,388.65 as of
10:23 a.m. local time, after falling as much as 0.3 percent. All
but five stocks advanced in the 45-member gauge.  The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index of H shares of
Chinese companies advanced 1 percent to 12,627.06.  Futures on the  Hang Seng Index  climbed 0.2 percent to
23,349. The HSI Volatility Index, the benchmark gauge for Hong
Kong stock options, slid 1.4 percent to 18.46.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
